1
00:03:26,640 --> 00:03:29,438
<i>This was my body.</i>

2
00:03:38,840 --> 00:03:44,790
<i>On December 27, 1979,</i>
<i>I lay in bed all day.</i>

3
00:03:44,920 --> 00:03:50,870
<i>Whether I was asleep or in a coma</i>
<i>later became a subject of dispute.</i>

4
00:03:54,160 --> 00:03:56,469
<i>When my breathing</i>
<i>became obstructed...</i>

5
00:03:56,600 --> 00:03:57,669
Maria!

6
00:03:57,800 --> 00:04:00,872
<i>... my husband, Claus von Bulow,</i>

7
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:04,993
<i>finally did as my maid</i>
<i>had been urging all day:</i>

8
00:04:05,120 --> 00:04:07,031
<i>he summoned a physician.</i>

9
00:04:07,160 --> 00:04:08,149
Dr. Paultees?

10
00:04:08,280 --> 00:04:12,876
<i>I stopped breathing.</i>
<i>My heart stopped beating.</i>

11
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:16,356
<i>By this time,</i>
<i>I was certainly in a deep coma</i>

12
00:04:16,480 --> 00:04:19,836
<i>from which I awoke several hours later.</i>

13
00:04:19,960 --> 00:04:23,111
<i>By the next morning,</i>
<i>I was myself again.</i>

14
00:04:23,240 --> 00:04:28,519
There's no reason for all this fuss.
I never felt better in my whole life.

15
00:04:28,640 --> 00:04:31,757
<i>This first coma aroused</i>
<i>suspicion and fear</i>

16
00:04:31,880 --> 00:04:34,952
<i>in the minds of my personal maid Maria,</i>

17
00:04:35,080 --> 00:04:38,834
<i>my son Alex,</i>
<i>and my elder daughter Ala.</i>

18
00:04:38,960 --> 00:04:43,272
<i>From this time on, though they never</i>
<i>voiced their suspicions to me,</i>

19
00:04:43,400 --> 00:04:47,075
<i>they kept a vigilant eye on Claus.</i>

20
00:04:47,200 --> 00:04:53,389
<i>A year later, just before Christmas,</i>
<i>their darkest fears seemed justified.</i>

21
00:04:53,520 --> 00:04:58,071
- Has Mummy had breakfast yet?
- No, we haven't seen her.

22
00:05:12,040 --> 00:05:15,999
<i>My husband did not want our daughter</i>
<i>Cosima to see what he had found,</i>

23
00:05:16,120 --> 00:05:18,839
<i>so he motioned to his stepson Alex.</i>

24
00:05:32,640 --> 00:05:36,349
<i>Second coma. My pulse was 38,</i>

25
00:05:36,480 --> 00:05:40,155
<i>my temperature 81.6 degrees.</i>

26
00:05:42,400 --> 00:05:44,709
Did you call an ambulance?

27
00:05:46,520 --> 00:05:51,913
Nicholas, ask Robert to open the main
gates. We're expecting an ambulance.

28
00:05:52,040 --> 00:05:55,396
Send an ambulance immediately...

29
00:05:55,520 --> 00:05:59,035
Keep her in something warm.
A blanket or anything you can find.

30
00:05:59,160 --> 00:06:02,232
<i>All this activity was pointless.</i>

31
00:06:03,880 --> 00:06:05,074
We'd better do an EEG.

32
00:06:05,200 --> 00:06:09,557
<i>I never woke from this coma,</i>
<i>and I never will.</i>

33
00:06:10,560 --> 00:06:15,839
<i>I am what doctors call</i>
<i>"persistent vegetative", a vegetable.</i>

34
00:06:17,120 --> 00:06:22,194
<i>According to medical experts, I could</i>
<i>stay like this for a very long time,</i>

35
00:06:22,320 --> 00:06:25,596
<i>brain-dead, body better than ever.</i>

36
00:06:27,360 --> 00:06:32,878
<i>Enter Robert Brillhoffer,</i>
<i>former Manhattan district attorney.</i>

37
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:37,471
<i>My two children from my first marriage,</i>
<i>Alex and Ala von Auersberg,</i>

38
00:06:37,600 --> 00:06:41,479
<i>hired Brillhoffer to investigate the case.</i>

39
00:06:42,520 --> 00:06:45,717
He put a "do not resuscitate" order
on her hospital chart.

40
00:06:45,840 --> 00:06:48,752
<i>They sent Alex</i>
<i>and a private investigator</i>

41
00:06:48,880 --> 00:06:54,318
<i>back to my Newport cottage,</i>
<i>Clarendon Court, to search for drugs.</i>

42
00:06:56,680 --> 00:07:00,798
<i>They found plenty... in Claus's closet.</i>

43
00:07:00,920 --> 00:07:03,559
<i>On top of that, the hospital lab reported</i>

44
00:07:03,680 --> 00:07:08,629
<i>that my blood insulin on admission</i>
<i>was 14 times normal,</i>

45
00:07:08,760 --> 00:07:12,958
<i>a level almost surely caused by injection.</i>

46
00:07:13,080 --> 00:07:17,039
<i>Insulin injection could</i>
<i>readily cause coma...</i>

47
00:07:17,720 --> 00:07:19,676
<i>or death.</i>

48
00:07:20,760 --> 00:07:24,639
<i>This encrusted needle</i>
<i>tested positive for insulin.</i>

49
00:07:26,160 --> 00:07:30,278
<i>Alex couldn't wait to get back</i>
<i>and show Brillhoffer.</i>

50
00:07:31,320 --> 00:07:33,629
<i>Now they felt they had</i>
<i>the murder weapon.</i>

51
00:07:33,760 --> 00:07:35,910
<i>All they lacked was the motive.</i>

52
00:07:36,680 --> 00:07:40,036
<i>At that moment, my husband</i>
<i>was vacationing with his mistress,</i>

53
00:07:40,160 --> 00:07:44,790
<i>the very beautiful soap-opera actress,</i>
<i>Alexandra Isles.</i>

54
00:07:44,920 --> 00:07:45,875
Oh, God!

55
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:51,950
<i>Mrs. Isles, a divorcée, was the daughter</i>
<i>of an old friend, Count Billy Botsky.</i>

56
00:07:55,360 --> 00:07:58,352
<i>Brillhoffer also discovered</i>
<i>that, at my death,</i>

57
00:07:58,480 --> 00:08:02,439
<i>Claus, whose own net worth</i>
<i>was only a million dollars,</i>

58
00:08:02,560 --> 00:08:06,235
<i>stood to inherit 14 million from me.</i>

59
00:08:06,360 --> 00:08:12,879
<i>Alexandra later testified that Claus</i>
<i>showed her a legal analysis of my will.</i>

60
00:08:14,280 --> 00:08:19,229
<i>On the evidence collected by Alex,</i>
<i>Ala and their lawyer Brillhoffer,</i>

61
00:08:19,360 --> 00:08:24,673
<i>my husband was accused of twice trying</i>
<i>to murder me with injections of insulin.</i>

62
00:08:24,800 --> 00:08:30,238
<i>On March 16, 1982, he was</i>
<i>found guilty on both counts.</i>

63
00:08:30,360 --> 00:08:33,397
<i>...</i> committed
on December 27, 1979...

64
00:08:33,520 --> 00:08:37,513
<i>Even Alexandra Isles</i>
<i>testified against him.</i>

65
00:08:37,640 --> 00:08:38,675
Guilty.

66
00:08:38,800 --> 00:08:43,271
As to count two, charged the defendant
committed on December 21, 1980,

67
00:08:43,400 --> 00:08:45,595
a crime of assault with intent to murder.

68
00:08:45,720 --> 00:08:47,312
- How do you find?
- Guilty.

69
00:08:47,440 --> 00:08:51,433
<i>You are about to see how</i>
<i>Claus von Bulow sought to reverse</i>

70
00:08:51,560 --> 00:08:54,597
<i>or escape from that jury's verdict.</i>

71
00:08:55,800 --> 00:08:57,756
<i>You tell me.</i>

72
00:09:03,440 --> 00:09:08,639
And two! Here it comes. Here we go,
taking you downtown! And Dersh...

73
00:09:10,080 --> 00:09:13,595
Take it in! Foul! OK, here I go.

74
00:09:13,720 --> 00:09:16,314
Watch the hands! Watch the hands!

75
00:09:21,960 --> 00:09:24,235
Yeah, hello.

76
00:09:24,360 --> 00:09:26,316
What?

77
00:09:28,320 --> 00:09:30,595
Oh, shit... Bottom line.

78
00:09:31,520 --> 00:09:32,555
Aw, shit!

79
00:09:52,960 --> 00:09:54,632
Hi.

80
00:10:00,400 --> 00:10:03,551
Let's try that again.
Hi, Dad. Remember Maggie?

81
00:10:04,720 --> 00:10:06,790
Hi, Maggie.

82
00:10:08,840 --> 00:10:12,150
They're gonna fry. The Johnson brothers.

83
00:10:12,280 --> 00:10:15,477
What? But...

84
00:10:16,840 --> 00:10:19,308
Two black kids broke
their father out of prison.

85
00:10:19,440 --> 00:10:22,398
The father shot two people:
the sons are convicted of murder.

86
00:10:22,520 --> 00:10:24,670
A lawyer prays for an innocent client.

87
00:10:24,800 --> 00:10:28,156
Finally, I get two.
Both of them are gonna get zapped.

88
00:10:28,280 --> 00:10:30,794
- No more appeals?
- This was the best shot.

89
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:35,116
Whoa. It's the press.

90
00:10:35,240 --> 00:10:37,549
<i>You</i> don't want to talk to the press?

91
00:10:38,920 --> 00:10:41,957
Dershowitz Psychiatric Institute.

92
00:10:42,760 --> 00:10:44,432
Hang on a second.

93
00:10:44,560 --> 00:10:47,074
Claus von Bulow.

94
00:10:47,200 --> 00:10:50,670
- It's a reporter.
- With an English accent?

95
00:10:50,800 --> 00:10:53,314
What paper do you represent?

96
00:10:53,440 --> 00:10:56,113
If I can't save two innocent kids,
what's the point?

97
00:10:56,240 --> 00:10:58,151
Yeah, one second. Sorry.

98
00:10:58,280 --> 00:11:00,396
He really seems to think he's von Bulow.

99
00:11:00,520 --> 00:11:04,513
Hello. This is Alan Dershowitz.
Who are you? What do you want?

100
00:11:07,480 --> 00:11:10,597
- It <i>is</i> von Bulow.
- Back in business.

101
00:11:17,240 --> 00:11:18,992
- Can I help you?
- Claus von Bulow?

102
00:11:19,120 --> 00:11:21,156
Elevators to the left.

103
00:11:28,040 --> 00:11:29,996
Holy shit.

104
00:11:37,200 --> 00:11:39,156
Hello?

105
00:11:44,480 --> 00:11:46,436
Hello?

106
00:11:46,640 --> 00:11:50,189
Professor Dershowitz. Hello, hello.

107
00:11:50,320 --> 00:11:53,596
- How good of you to come.
- Pleasure.

108
00:11:53,720 --> 00:11:55,711
Won't you sit down?

109
00:12:02,480 --> 00:12:05,040
- Do you play?
- That? No.

110
00:12:06,200 --> 00:12:11,593
Most people think it's a game of luck.
Actually, it's largely a matter of nerve.

111
00:12:15,120 --> 00:12:18,635
Erm... Nothing, thank you, Charles.

112
00:12:19,240 --> 00:12:22,949
Why don't we go to Delmonico's
and have a proper lunch?

113
00:12:23,080 --> 00:12:24,638
Whatever.

114
00:12:28,280 --> 00:12:30,430
I have the greatest respect

115
00:12:30,560 --> 00:12:34,519
for the intelligence and integrity
of the Jewish people.

116
00:12:37,080 --> 00:12:40,629
When I married Sunny, she was
the most beautiful divorcée in the world,

117
00:12:40,760 --> 00:12:42,512
and one of the wealthiest.

118
00:12:42,640 --> 00:12:45,791
Even so, we never got <i>this</i> table.

119
00:12:45,920 --> 00:12:47,911
Professor Dershowitz.

120
00:12:50,280 --> 00:12:52,635
Dr. von Bulow.

121
00:12:52,760 --> 00:12:55,593
Two injections of insulin,
already I'm a doctor.

122
00:12:55,720 --> 00:12:58,951
In America, it's fame rather than class.

123
00:12:59,080 --> 00:13:04,552
Now, after all this unpleasantness,
I always get the best table.

124
00:13:05,920 --> 00:13:11,631
- Speaking of the unpleasantness...
- Oh, yes. We'd better discuss your fee.

125
00:13:11,760 --> 00:13:15,389
OK. $300 an hour.

126
00:13:15,560 --> 00:13:17,710
Good Lord.

127
00:13:17,840 --> 00:13:21,515
You know, I used to be a lawyer
in London. That sounds a bit steep.

128
00:13:21,640 --> 00:13:25,599
It's average for a case like this.
Besides, I do a lot of pro bono work.

129
00:13:25,720 --> 00:13:28,871
You'd pay for that. Plus,
I have to pay students, associates.

130
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:34,074
Are you saying that if I agree to pay 300,
you will handle my appeal?

131
00:13:34,200 --> 00:13:37,556
No, not so far.
Doesn't look like my kind of case.

132
00:13:38,960 --> 00:13:43,112
I'm not a hired gun. I gotta feel a moral
or constitutional issue is at stake.

133
00:13:43,240 --> 00:13:45,834
But I'm absolutely innocent.

134
00:13:45,960 --> 00:13:49,635
And my civil liberties have
been egregiously violated.

135
00:13:49,760 --> 00:13:54,675
Two black kids are facing the electric
chair for a crime they did not commit.

136
00:13:54,800 --> 00:13:56,756
<i>They</i> are innocent.

137
00:13:58,120 --> 00:14:02,113
Well, before you assume I'm guilty,
won't you hear my story?

138
00:14:02,240 --> 00:14:07,314
No. Never let defendants explain. Puts
most of them in an awkward position.

139
00:14:07,440 --> 00:14:10,034
- How do you mean?
- Lying.

140
00:14:11,840 --> 00:14:14,274
But I give you my word as a gentleman.

141
00:14:15,280 --> 00:14:17,748
Oh. Well...

142
00:14:21,840 --> 00:14:27,551
Won't you at least read the record
and see if you can find something...

143
00:14:29,400 --> 00:14:31,356
constitutional?

144
00:14:33,520 --> 00:14:35,750
You do have one thing in your favor.

145
00:14:37,840 --> 00:14:40,070
Everybody hates you.

146
00:14:45,160 --> 00:14:47,071
Well, that's a start.

147
00:14:47,200 --> 00:14:50,397
Come on, Maxwell.
Yeah! Come on, Max.

148
00:14:50,520 --> 00:14:52,715
It was a hit! Yes!

149
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:58,514
- So, what do you think?
- Oh, he did it. He did it.

150
00:14:58,640 --> 00:15:02,758
- Of course he did it. Can we win?
- A hundred to one against.

151
00:15:02,880 --> 00:15:06,793
The maid schmeared him on both comas.
Look at this. It says here...

152
00:15:06,920 --> 00:15:11,198
After you realized that Mrs. von Bulow
had not gotten up, what did you do?

153
00:15:11,320 --> 00:15:13,550
I came downstairs,

154
00:15:13,680 --> 00:15:17,468
and Mr. von Bulow said that
Madame had a very sore throat,

155
00:15:17,600 --> 00:15:22,549
<i>and I didn't have to do any work,</i>
<i>and she was in bed all day.</i>

156
00:15:33,840 --> 00:15:37,913
What are you doing? Did we ring for you?

157
00:15:44,680 --> 00:15:46,910
She's ice-cold.

158
00:15:47,040 --> 00:15:49,235
Madame. Mrs. von Bulow!

159
00:15:49,360 --> 00:15:55,356
Leave her alone. She's sleeping. She
drank last night. We didn't get any rest.

160
00:15:55,480 --> 00:16:00,270
She's not sleeping. She's unconscious.

161
00:16:01,240 --> 00:16:04,312
- You must call a doctor.
- Maria!

162
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:08,195
Go on.

163
00:16:16,640 --> 00:16:19,313
<i> A half-hour later,</i>
<i>she had not moved.</i>

164
00:16:19,440 --> 00:16:22,079
<i>I went back and forth all morning.</i>

165
00:16:23,800 --> 00:16:28,828
<i>Finally, mid-afternoon,</i>
<i>Mr. von Bulow spoke to Dr. Paultees.</i>

166
00:16:28,960 --> 00:16:31,235
<i>But he lied to doctor.</i>

167
00:16:31,360 --> 00:16:35,512
She's sleeping now, but earlier she was
up to the bathroom and had a soft drink,

168
00:16:35,640 --> 00:16:37,710
so there's no cause for alarm...

169
00:16:37,840 --> 00:16:41,515
<i> But she never moved.</i>
<i>Never got up.</i>

170
00:16:41,640 --> 00:16:45,758
<i>She was lying</i>
<i>in the same position all day.</i>

171
00:16:45,880 --> 00:16:51,034
<i>Later her heart stops, and</i>
<i>Dr. Paultees, he comes and saves her.</i>

172
00:16:51,160 --> 00:16:54,072
<i>After they go to the hospital,</i>
<i>I change the sheets.</i>

173
00:16:54,200 --> 00:16:56,760
<i>I find a puddle of urine.</i>

174
00:16:56,880 --> 00:17:01,078
<i>If Madame went to the bathroom,</i>
<i>she would not have peed in her bed.</i>

175
00:17:01,200 --> 00:17:03,998
Right.
Why would Claus lie about that?

176
00:17:04,120 --> 00:17:08,477
It's suspicious but hardly criminal.
How about the second coma?

177
00:17:08,600 --> 00:17:12,912
Maria wasn't in Newport for that one.
But shortly before the second coma...

178
00:17:13,040 --> 00:17:16,749
<i> I'm cleaning up their room</i>
<i>when I find Mr. von Bulow's canvas bag</i>

179
00:17:16,880 --> 00:17:18,677
<i>packed for Newport.</i>

180
00:17:18,800 --> 00:17:22,031
<i>Inside, there's a little black bag.</i>

181
00:17:22,160 --> 00:17:25,596
<i>A bottle of insulin,</i>
<i>a syringe and needles.</i>

182
00:17:25,720 --> 00:17:28,393
Alexander! Alexander, come here!

183
00:17:31,880 --> 00:17:37,989
Insulin? For what, insulin?
My lady's not diabetic.

184
00:17:43,280 --> 00:17:46,238
<i> Three weeks later,</i>
<i>Sunny's lying unconscious</i>

185
00:17:46,360 --> 00:17:49,955
in a freezing bathroom with
her nightgown hiked over her waist.

186
00:17:50,080 --> 00:17:52,753
If I was on that jury,
I would've voted to convict.

187
00:17:52,880 --> 00:17:55,440
Then you're taking the case?

188
00:17:55,560 --> 00:17:57,869
Reminds me of my Hitler dream.

189
00:17:58,920 --> 00:18:02,310
Hitler calls up, he's alive, needs a lawyer.

190
00:18:02,440 --> 00:18:05,716
I say "Sure. Come on over."

191
00:18:05,840 --> 00:18:08,991
Then I have to decide:
do I take the case or do I kill him?

192
00:18:09,120 --> 00:18:11,076
You? No question.

193
00:18:11,200 --> 00:18:14,317
- I would take the case.
<i>- Then</i> kill him.

194
00:18:15,480 --> 00:18:17,630
I'm a maniac. I need your judgment,

195
00:18:17,760 --> 00:18:21,514
someone to watch what I'm doing and
occasionally remind me about the law.

196
00:18:21,640 --> 00:18:23,119
When can I see the transcripts?

197
00:18:23,240 --> 00:18:27,074
You're a former prosecutor, conservative.
We agree on nothing.

198
00:18:27,200 --> 00:18:31,079
But you're smarter than the DA. If I can
beat your arguments, I can destroy his.

199
00:18:31,200 --> 00:18:36,797
Rhode Island is corrupt. Everything is
political. I don't think that way. You do.

200
00:18:36,920 --> 00:18:40,276
I have to see the big picture.
I can't immerse myself in facts.

201
00:18:40,400 --> 00:18:42,311
But we must know the facts.

202
00:18:42,440 --> 00:18:46,433
No one can assimilate information
as quickly as you two.

203
00:18:46,560 --> 00:18:48,596
I agree with that assessment.

204
00:18:53,400 --> 00:18:56,119
- You're out of your mind.
- I only have 45 days to file.

205
00:18:56,240 --> 00:18:58,196
I can't do it without you.

206
00:18:59,680 --> 00:19:03,468
- I know you don't wanna come back...
- Is this strictly professional?

207
00:19:07,120 --> 00:19:09,315
It better be.

208
00:19:09,440 --> 00:19:12,796
That's wonderful. I want the best
people in the world on our side,

209
00:19:12,920 --> 00:19:14,638
the most prestigious experts.

210
00:19:14,760 --> 00:19:18,673
Nobel prize-winning scientists,
some of your colleagues at Harvard.

211
00:19:18,800 --> 00:19:22,190
Wait a minute, Claus.
We got a little problem, OK?

212
00:19:22,320 --> 00:19:24,356
People like that, we can't control.

213
00:19:24,480 --> 00:19:27,358
They find one incriminating fact,
they'll tell the world.

214
00:19:27,480 --> 00:19:30,597
I'm not afraid, Alan.
Let the chips fall where they may.

215
00:19:30,720 --> 00:19:34,030
That's what an innocent man would say.

216
00:19:34,160 --> 00:19:35,513
I know.

217
00:19:41,760 --> 00:19:43,751
That just came for you, Daddy.

218
00:19:45,040 --> 00:19:47,918
My daughter Cosima.
She never doubted me.

219
00:19:48,040 --> 00:19:53,990
She loves Alex and Ala dearly. Siding
with me has cost her their affections.

220
00:19:56,200 --> 00:19:58,839
I don't know what I would've done.

221
00:20:02,760 --> 00:20:06,230
I don't want to hear your story,
but I do need some information.

222
00:20:06,360 --> 00:20:08,555
Of course.

223
00:20:08,680 --> 00:20:13,071
I gather the older children deny Sunny
had a problem with pills and alcohol.

224
00:20:13,200 --> 00:20:14,792
Spectacular understatement.

225
00:20:14,920 --> 00:20:18,071
So there must be somebody
who saw it. A witness, a friend?

226
00:20:18,200 --> 00:20:19,599
- You want affidavits?
- Yes.

227
00:20:19,720 --> 00:20:21,472
- I'll get them.
- You'll get them.

228
00:20:21,600 --> 00:20:24,797
The drugs prescribed for <i>me</i>
were taken by Sunny.

229
00:20:24,920 --> 00:20:26,273
That's a lot of drugs.

230
00:20:26,400 --> 00:20:30,518
But the prosecution's allegation that
I knew about syringes, injections -

231
00:20:30,640 --> 00:20:32,551
totally accurate.

232
00:20:32,680 --> 00:20:37,071
Sunny and I gave ourselves B12 injections
in the late '60s. It was quite the fad.

233
00:20:37,200 --> 00:20:41,830
Can I explain something? The less I know
from you, the more options I have.

234
00:20:41,960 --> 00:20:46,511
When you tell me "the truth", you limit me
to a defense that fits with what you say.

235
00:20:46,640 --> 00:20:49,791
But isn't the truth the simplest way, Alan?

236
00:20:49,920 --> 00:20:55,199
I mean, why did I stay all day
at Sunny's side without calling a doctor?

237
00:20:55,320 --> 00:20:57,993
Because Sunny detested doctors.

238
00:20:58,120 --> 00:21:01,237
If we called one without her approval,
she went berserk.

239
00:21:01,360 --> 00:21:04,557
Once she broke her hip and
didn't go to hospital for two days.

240
00:21:04,680 --> 00:21:08,434
- Did you hear what I just said?
- Did you hear the judge sentence me?

241
00:21:08,560 --> 00:21:11,518
Sorry. 30 years is a pretty stiff sentence.

242
00:21:11,640 --> 00:21:15,553
Twice trying to murder one's wife,
anything less would be monstrous.

243
00:21:15,680 --> 00:21:20,595
But for a man like myself,
who did nothing...

244
00:21:23,720 --> 00:21:27,474
What I wanted to ask:
if we lose the appeal,

245
00:21:27,600 --> 00:21:33,709
will I have the chance later to set my
affairs in order before I'm incarcerated?

246
00:21:33,840 --> 00:21:39,790
In Europe, a gentleman is given
the opportunity to end things properly.

247
00:21:41,560 --> 00:21:46,759
- Come on, Claus.
- We are each the keeper of our own soul.

248
00:21:49,320 --> 00:21:54,269
Two big problems:
the case against him is very strong,

249
00:21:54,400 --> 00:21:59,269
and the legal conviction isn't the only
conviction that we've got to reverse.

250
00:21:59,400 --> 00:22:02,870
The more dangerous conviction
is the absolute certainty

251
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:05,719
of the American people
that Claus is guilty.

252
00:22:05,840 --> 00:22:09,355
Finding grounds for reversal
won't be enough here.

253
00:22:09,480 --> 00:22:11,516
Judges on the Rhode Island
Supreme Court

254
00:22:11,640 --> 00:22:15,792
will have to go home to their spouses
and explain why they reversed.

255
00:22:15,920 --> 00:22:22,234
To get them to do that, we have to
obliterate every aspect of the state's case.

256
00:22:22,360 --> 00:22:24,954
Destroy the medical case
and their witnesses,

257
00:22:25,080 --> 00:22:29,198
so the judges have
no possible way to affirm.

258
00:22:29,320 --> 00:22:31,993
Total victory,
or we are dead in the water.

259
00:22:32,120 --> 00:22:36,671
Now, I assume that you've all had
an opportunity to look at the transcripts.

260
00:22:36,800 --> 00:22:38,438
First impressions?

261
00:22:38,560 --> 00:22:43,475
I think this whole thing stinks.
I think Claus von Bulow stinks.

262
00:22:43,600 --> 00:22:46,797
He's obviously guilty of
something pretty despicable,

263
00:22:46,920 --> 00:22:52,711
and, if we free him, we become partners
in his crime, accessories after the fact.

264
00:22:52,840 --> 00:22:56,150
I'm shocked, with your record
defending the poor and oppressed,

265
00:22:56,280 --> 00:22:58,953
that you've taken this case.

266
00:23:00,920 --> 00:23:03,957
I won't have anything to do with it.

267
00:23:04,080 --> 00:23:08,039
And I hope my fellow students
won't, either. Goodbye.

268
00:23:08,800 --> 00:23:13,237
My I exercise my First Amendment
right to free speech?

269
00:23:15,080 --> 00:23:20,916
If lawyers only defended the innocent,
there'd be just ten lawyers in the country.

270
00:23:21,040 --> 00:23:23,679
Why help guilty people get off?

271
00:23:24,920 --> 00:23:27,036
You're sure he's guilty? 100% sure?

272
00:23:27,160 --> 00:23:31,711
He had a lawyer. He had a trial.
He was convicted.

273
00:23:31,840 --> 00:23:34,593
- Are you sure he had a fair trial?
- Come on!

274
00:23:34,720 --> 00:23:37,792
It's the basis of the whole legal system!

275
00:23:37,920 --> 00:23:41,276
Everyone gets a defense.

276
00:23:41,400 --> 00:23:47,316
So the system is there for the one
innocent person who was falsely accused.

277
00:23:47,440 --> 00:23:52,230
OK, look. Say it's you. OK?

278
00:23:52,360 --> 00:23:58,196
You decide to get a divorce.
You're gonna divorce your husband.

279
00:23:58,320 --> 00:24:01,915
A week later, you're accused
of molesting your son.

280
00:24:03,080 --> 00:24:06,470
Don't give me that look.
Stuff like this happens all the time.

281
00:24:06,600 --> 00:24:10,070
Suddenly, you're alone. You hate it.

282
00:24:10,200 --> 00:24:15,638
It's a nightmare.
Everyone assumes that you are guilty.

283
00:24:15,760 --> 00:24:19,639
Even the mailman is beginning
to look at you a little funny.

284
00:24:19,760 --> 00:24:22,433
You only got one person
who believes in you.

285
00:24:22,560 --> 00:24:26,599
There's only one person
you can trust: your lawyer.

286
00:24:27,400 --> 00:24:31,871
Yeah, OK. So, someone's
gotta defend Claus.

287
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:34,195
But why you? Why us?

288
00:24:35,440 --> 00:24:37,874
Look, you're my student.
You have a choice.

289
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:41,675
You don't have to do anything
you don't want to. That is your choice.

290
00:24:41,800 --> 00:24:45,554
The reason <i>I</i> take cases - and here
I'm unlike most other lawyers,

291
00:24:45,680 --> 00:24:48,433
who are not professors
and have to make a living -

292
00:24:48,560 --> 00:24:52,439
I take cases cos I get pissed off.

293
00:24:52,560 --> 00:24:54,949
And I am pissed off here.

294
00:24:55,080 --> 00:25:00,438
The family hired a private prosecutor.
Unacceptable!

295
00:25:00,560 --> 00:25:03,632
They conducted a private search!

296
00:25:03,760 --> 00:25:08,038
Now, we let 'em get away with that, rich
people won't go to the cops any more.

297
00:25:08,160 --> 00:25:13,109
You know what they'll do? Get
their own lawyers to collect evidence.

298
00:25:13,240 --> 00:25:16,516
And then they are going
to choose which evidence

299
00:25:16,640 --> 00:25:18,995
they feel like passing on to the DA.

300
00:25:19,120 --> 00:25:22,510
And the next victim isn't
gonna be rich like von Bulow,

301
00:25:22,640 --> 00:25:29,352
but is gonna be some poor schnook who
can't afford or can't find a decent lawyer.

302
00:25:34,920 --> 00:25:39,710
I think it's a little more complicated
than your simple moral superiority.

303
00:25:41,520 --> 00:25:42,999
No?

304
00:25:43,120 --> 00:25:47,193
I agree von Bulow is guilty, but that's
the fun. I mean, that's the challenge.

305
00:25:47,320 --> 00:25:49,993
See? Now, <i>there</i> is a lawyer.

306
00:25:51,320 --> 00:25:53,834
- What?
<i>- I have Mr. von Bulow for you.</i>

307
00:25:53,960 --> 00:25:56,076
OK, put him on.

308
00:25:56,200 --> 00:26:01,035
Alan, a rather unsavory character
called David Marriott contacted me,

309
00:26:01,160 --> 00:26:05,392
claiming to have information about
a drug delivery at Clarendon Court.

310
00:26:05,520 --> 00:26:08,114
- OK. Where does he live?
- Somewhere in Wakefield.

311
00:26:08,240 --> 00:26:10,196
OK, we'll get on it.

312
00:26:10,920 --> 00:26:14,708
Tom, I want you to get
a private investigator

313
00:26:14,840 --> 00:26:18,515
to dig into a David Marriott,
lives in Wakefield.

314
00:26:19,560 --> 00:26:23,348
- OK. How are we gonna win this case?
- The judge made lots of mistakes.

315
00:26:23,480 --> 00:26:26,074
Judges always make mistakes.
How will we win?

316
00:26:26,200 --> 00:26:28,668
One issue leaps up.
This lawyer, Brillhoffer,

317
00:26:28,800 --> 00:26:32,873
interviewed Alex, Maria, everybody.
He was the first to hear their stories.

318
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:36,151
He took notes and used them at trial
against a defense witness.

319
00:26:36,280 --> 00:26:39,955
But the defense never saw the notes.
The judge wouldn't let us have them.

320
00:26:40,080 --> 00:26:42,310
It's perfect <i>Brady.</i>

321
00:26:42,440 --> 00:26:45,796
OK, why don't you draft a letter,
writing to Brillhoffer,

322
00:26:45,920 --> 00:26:48,354
asking him very nicely
to send us his notes?

323
00:26:48,480 --> 00:26:52,632
- Yeah, right. He'll fax them right over.
- Yeah, right.

324
00:26:52,760 --> 00:26:54,796
We could win on this issue alone.

325
00:26:54,920 --> 00:26:58,356
You know it, I know it.
Just make sure <i>he</i> knows it.

326
00:26:58,480 --> 00:27:01,392
- Now, Nancy and Dobbs.
- Yes?

327
00:27:01,520 --> 00:27:04,557
They're going to attack
the medical testimony.

328
00:27:04,680 --> 00:27:07,752
Our Rhode Island counsel,
Peter Macintosh,

329
00:27:07,880 --> 00:27:10,348
he will analyze the state supreme court.

330
00:27:10,480 --> 00:27:15,076
The rest of us should begin dissecting
the transcript. Errors, inconsistencies.

331
00:27:15,200 --> 00:27:20,957
OK, great. Now remember, most cases
are won in the field, not in court.

332
00:27:21,680 --> 00:27:23,636
Minnie?

333
00:27:24,680 --> 00:27:26,989
You wanna work with Sarah on this?

334
00:27:27,120 --> 00:27:30,715
- You may learn something.
- Come on, Minnie.

335
00:27:30,840 --> 00:27:32,193
Minnie!

336
00:27:32,320 --> 00:27:35,357
- Please?
- Come on.

337
00:27:36,240 --> 00:27:40,392
I don't trust Marriott. I don't know him.
But if he knew Alex von Auersberg...

338
00:27:40,520 --> 00:27:44,035
You're crazy. I don't know who
you think you are. Perry Mason?

339
00:27:44,160 --> 00:27:48,551
Let our private investigator interview him.
It's stupid and unprofessional.

340
00:27:48,680 --> 00:27:51,478
- It's fun.
- Fun? This guy is a sleaze.

341
00:27:51,600 --> 00:27:55,593
- You don't know what he's gonna try.
- What, is he gonna shoot me?

342
00:27:55,720 --> 00:27:57,676
Come on, I'm from Brooklyn.

343
00:28:03,080 --> 00:28:07,949
OK, I'll stand by the window every ten
minutes. That way you can know I'm safe.

344
00:28:09,480 --> 00:28:14,918
I had this friend, Gilbert Jackson.
Interior decorator.

345
00:28:15,040 --> 00:28:17,873
Flaming queen,
but a very excellent guy.

346
00:28:19,960 --> 00:28:22,428
He introduced me to Alex von Auersberg.

347
00:28:23,400 --> 00:28:25,197
Sure it was Alex?

348
00:28:25,320 --> 00:28:30,713
We had dinner a few times, drinks.
All I knew, Alex was some rich kid.

349
00:28:31,720 --> 00:28:36,236
So sometimes - this is like summer of '77-

350
00:28:36,360 --> 00:28:38,794
I'd motor to Newport for some R and R.

351
00:28:38,920 --> 00:28:41,275
Gilbert asked me to bring Alex a package.

352
00:28:42,280 --> 00:28:46,159
I figured interior decoration.
Maybe drapes.

353
00:28:46,280 --> 00:28:48,748
Like six times. So I'd call Alex.

354
00:28:48,880 --> 00:28:51,952
- How did you get his phone number?
- From Gilbert.

355
00:28:52,080 --> 00:28:54,514
- You still have it?
- Maybe.

356
00:28:55,480 --> 00:28:57,550
I'm that kind of guy.

357
00:29:22,160 --> 00:29:24,116
Here.

358
00:29:29,240 --> 00:29:33,199
One night, I got curious.
Opened the package.

359
00:29:34,080 --> 00:29:39,200
Fuckin' pharmacy, man.
Needles, syringes, white powder,

360
00:29:39,320 --> 00:29:43,598
nice selection of pills, Demerol...
Like a drugstore.

361
00:29:45,480 --> 00:29:49,519
You delivered drugs six times
and didn't know it?

362
00:29:51,200 --> 00:29:54,954
Stupid, huh?
Then Gilbert asked me again.

363
00:29:55,800 --> 00:30:00,237
I couldn't say no, but this time I made
Alex open the package in front of me.

364
00:30:00,360 --> 00:30:02,316
Voilà.

365
00:30:03,440 --> 00:30:06,477
I go "Awful lot of pharmaceuticals
for one person."

366
00:30:06,600 --> 00:30:10,434
He goes "Oh, I give some
to my mom to keep her off my back."

367
00:30:12,160 --> 00:30:15,709
A few weeks later,
Gilbert gets mistaken for a softball.

368
00:30:15,840 --> 00:30:20,550
Two guys bash his head in.
Alex calls me, totally urinary.

369
00:30:20,680 --> 00:30:25,356
Will the cops find his phone number
and fuck up his trust fund or something?

370
00:30:25,480 --> 00:30:31,032
Well, that's the fat. That's the skinny.
You like it?

371
00:30:33,160 --> 00:30:35,674
You traffic with drug dealers
and drag queens,

372
00:30:35,800 --> 00:30:38,678
you have a part-time job,
you ride in rented limos.

373
00:30:38,800 --> 00:30:43,476
All in all, I'd say you're probably the least
impressive witness I've ever seen.

374
00:30:43,600 --> 00:30:46,068
Wait a minute.

375
00:30:48,520 --> 00:30:51,671
You think I'm scum, don't you?

376
00:30:51,800 --> 00:30:55,076
Blow it out your ass.

377
00:30:55,200 --> 00:30:58,829
You want a witness to back me up?
I'll get one.

378
00:30:58,960 --> 00:31:02,919
And hey, maybe I'll see you
at the Celtics, huh?

379
00:31:14,040 --> 00:31:17,635
I am not going to let them execute you.
You're not gonna die.

380
00:31:17,760 --> 00:31:22,356
Look, Johnny, this is gonna be
a lot easier on you if you don't cry, OK?

381
00:31:22,480 --> 00:31:25,677
I... I know your brother's hysterical.

382
00:31:25,800 --> 00:31:28,553
Number one, they always
set a date for the execution,

383
00:31:28,680 --> 00:31:30,671
and they always postpone it.

384
00:31:30,800 --> 00:31:36,113
He's great like this. I just wish he had
something left for those around him.

385
00:31:36,240 --> 00:31:38,800
Why are you talking to me about money?

386
00:31:38,920 --> 00:31:41,559
Anyway, it's nice to have you back here.

387
00:31:42,440 --> 00:31:44,396
Say hello to your brother.

388
00:31:44,520 --> 00:31:46,750
Right. OK.

389
00:31:54,680 --> 00:31:57,069
OK, who's got what?

390
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:03,755
Maria's testimony. She says Sunny
did take Valium prescribed for Claus.

391
00:32:03,880 --> 00:32:05,598
Score one for von Bulow.

392
00:32:05,720 --> 00:32:08,871
- And this Jamie Smather prescription?
- Who's Jamie Smather?

393
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:14,074
300-pound red-headed hooker in white
boots. She supplied Claus with Valium.

394
00:32:14,200 --> 00:32:16,794
He had a gorgeous mistress
and went to an ugly whore?

395
00:32:16,920 --> 00:32:19,878
There are some things
even mistresses won't do.

396
00:32:21,800 --> 00:32:24,268
- Like what?
- I am not telling.

397
00:32:25,720 --> 00:32:30,396
Anyway, Maria swears she first saw
this Jamie Smather prescription

398
00:32:30,520 --> 00:32:34,195
February 14th,
and then again February 28th.

399
00:32:34,320 --> 00:32:37,153
- So?
- It wasn't prescribed till the 28th.

400
00:32:37,280 --> 00:32:39,714
You're not suggesting she's lying?

401
00:32:39,840 --> 00:32:42,559
How about Maria's insulin?
Anything more on that?

402
00:32:42,680 --> 00:32:44,636
Not yet.

403
00:32:45,600 --> 00:32:48,353
Something about that bothers me.

404
00:32:49,240 --> 00:32:53,552
- OK, who's next?
- Brillhoffer wrote back.

405
00:32:53,680 --> 00:32:55,716
He's very attached to his notes.

406
00:32:58,440 --> 00:33:02,752
"I am satisfied that there is not
a scrap of paper in my files

407
00:33:02,880 --> 00:33:05,872
that might even arguably
be viewed as exculpatory."

408
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:10,596
- Translation?
- He says he has nothing that'd help us.

409
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:14,230
- You with me?
- Pay dirt.

410
00:33:14,360 --> 00:33:16,237
- What?
- He's a lawyer.

411
00:33:16,360 --> 00:33:19,158
If he didn't have anything,
he'd give it to us.

412
00:33:19,280 --> 00:33:22,477
But there's something there,
and he'll fight to hold on to it.

413
00:33:22,600 --> 00:33:26,309
I will bet my fee that no one
remembered seeing insulin

414
00:33:26,440 --> 00:33:28,476
until after the lab report came back.

415
00:33:28,600 --> 00:33:31,592
- So you're suggesting...
- Memory enhancement.

416
00:33:31,720 --> 00:33:34,792
- It might be more than that.
- Possibly.

417
00:33:35,840 --> 00:33:39,150
- A frame-up.
- You mean, by the kids?

418
00:33:39,280 --> 00:33:42,829
- Where d'you get this? Brillhoffer's letter?
- Pure deduction.

419
00:33:42,960 --> 00:33:47,954
A good lawyer is part psychiatrist,
detective, logician.

420
00:33:48,080 --> 00:33:52,039
- A great lawyer...
- Never would have taken this case.

421
00:33:52,680 --> 00:33:56,832
If there's nothing more...
Has anybody read this?

422
00:33:57,960 --> 00:34:00,155
It's an interview with Truman Capote.

423
00:34:00,280 --> 00:34:05,115
He says, when she was 19, Sunny von
Bulow taught him how to inject drugs.

424
00:34:05,240 --> 00:34:06,514
Let me see that.

425
00:34:09,200 --> 00:34:14,991
- Well, well, well. The famous professor.
- My new girlfriend, Andrea Reynolds.

426
00:34:15,120 --> 00:34:18,271
- I'm not his girlfriend. I'm his savior.
- Perfectly true.

427
00:34:18,400 --> 00:34:23,315
Two days after the trial, we fell in love.
It was really very dramatic.

428
00:34:23,440 --> 00:34:25,396
Andrea, Andrea, Andrea, come on.

429
00:34:26,080 --> 00:34:29,197
Since then, I've devoted my life
to clearing his name.

430
00:34:29,320 --> 00:34:31,959
I made him hire you.

431
00:34:33,080 --> 00:34:35,355
"Get the Jew," I said.

432
00:34:36,160 --> 00:34:37,991
Darling...

433
00:34:38,120 --> 00:34:40,873
Can the Jew get down to business?

434
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:44,231
We've got an affidavit. Smythe.

435
00:34:44,360 --> 00:34:49,718
Mrs. Ruth Smythe gave us an affidavit
corroborating Truman Capote.

436
00:34:49,840 --> 00:34:51,910
I have affidavits, too.

437
00:34:53,520 --> 00:34:56,717
Newport people.
They describe Sunny taking pills,

438
00:34:56,840 --> 00:34:58,796
getting drunk and falling down,

439
00:34:58,920 --> 00:35:02,310
thumping into doorways,
smearing lipstick all over her face.

440
00:35:02,440 --> 00:35:05,352
- Not a very pretty picture.
- She did it, didn't she?

441
00:35:05,480 --> 00:35:07,436
Don't be a priss.

442
00:35:08,480 --> 00:35:11,313
- Sunny was a lovely woman.
- Spoiled rotten.

443
00:35:11,440 --> 00:35:14,910
Yes, but lovely. Till she drank.

444
00:35:15,440 --> 00:35:18,876
Two drinks, and she became...
nasty, irrational.

445
00:35:19,000 --> 00:35:22,356
All women are irrational.
Did we mention the priest?

446
00:35:22,480 --> 00:35:28,430
Oh. Marriott apparently confided
in a priest, who's consented to talk to us.

447
00:35:31,320 --> 00:35:33,709
Father Capello from Providence.

448
00:35:35,200 --> 00:35:40,149
A priest? A priest is the ideal witness.
It's like getting the word of God.

449
00:35:40,280 --> 00:35:42,874
