908
01:14:20,600 --> 01:14:26,550
I'm going to Europe in the new year.
This will probably lead to a split.

909
01:14:26,680 --> 01:14:28,830
Oh.

910
01:14:28,960 --> 01:14:31,554
It's all right. She'll get over it.

911
01:14:34,000 --> 01:14:36,309
Alex says you said that the next day.

912
01:14:36,440 --> 01:14:40,353
Is anything more absurd than announcing
your intention to divorce a woman

913
01:14:40,480 --> 01:14:42,436
who's just fallen into a coma?

914
01:14:42,560 --> 01:14:47,759
<i>No. That evening everything</i>
<i>seemed normal enough.</i>

915
01:14:47,880 --> 01:14:53,238
<i>Not cheerful. But then, we didn't</i>
<i>usually giggle at mealtimes.</i>

916
01:14:53,360 --> 01:14:56,113
<i>Despite her doctor's warnings</i>
<i>about sweets,</i>

917
01:14:56,240 --> 01:14:59,949
<i>the only thing Sunny consumed</i>
<i>was a sundae.</i>

918
01:15:10,400 --> 01:15:15,235
<i>After supper, I went to finish off</i>
<i>some work in my study.</i>

919
01:15:15,360 --> 01:15:18,750
<i>The others decided to</i>
<i>chat in the living room.</i>

920
01:15:18,880 --> 01:15:24,159
That would be lovely, but first
I need to go to my room for just a minute.

921
01:15:37,600 --> 01:15:40,797
<i>After about an hour, I dropped in on them.</i>

922
01:15:44,400 --> 01:15:46,834
Darling, would you care for anything?

923
01:15:47,880 --> 01:15:50,189
Mm...

924
01:15:50,320 --> 01:15:55,155
lf... there's some...
chicken bouillon left.

925
01:15:59,120 --> 01:16:01,076
I'll look.

926
01:16:14,800 --> 01:16:16,995
There you are, darling.

927
01:16:25,720 --> 01:16:27,836
Thank you.

928
01:16:34,640 --> 01:16:36,835
How is your work coming?

929
01:16:36,960 --> 01:16:41,988
I'm totally flummoxed. I can't
get the figures to make any sense.

930
01:16:43,360 --> 01:16:49,469
- Why don't you call your friend Deborah?
- I doubt she'd be in Saturday night.

931
01:16:52,320 --> 01:16:56,313
So, Deborah, I think you'll agree
that's 7-2-8. Right. Now...

932
01:16:56,440 --> 01:17:01,070
<i>But Deborah was home,</i>
<i>and we did talk for some time, until...</i>

933
01:17:01,200 --> 01:17:04,033
Claus, come quick. Mummy's not well.

934
01:17:04,160 --> 01:17:06,958
Deborah, can I call you back
in the morning? Thanks.

935
01:17:07,080 --> 01:17:11,039
Her voice got very weak, and she
almost fell down. I had to help her.

936
01:17:20,440 --> 01:17:22,715
Somebody open a window.

937
01:17:25,520 --> 01:17:27,988
I find the chill reassuring.

938
01:17:32,080 --> 01:17:33,752
Now I must speak with Claus.

939
01:17:33,880 --> 01:17:36,633
- Good night, Mummy.
- Good night.

940
01:17:39,920 --> 01:17:41,876
Good night, darling.

941
01:17:43,960 --> 01:17:45,916
Good night, Alex.

942
01:17:56,000 --> 01:17:58,195
That is, if Claus has <i>time</i> to talk.

943
01:17:58,800 --> 01:18:04,432
Or are you going to work every spare
moment right through Christmas?

944
01:18:05,600 --> 01:18:09,115
Is your work so fascinating?
Or are you trying to drive me away?

945
01:18:09,240 --> 01:18:13,313
Because if you are, you're succeeding,
because I don't want this.

946
01:18:13,440 --> 01:18:16,910
I didn't marry you for this.
I could've had anybody.

947
01:18:17,040 --> 01:18:19,110
With my money? Anybody!

948
01:18:20,080 --> 01:18:23,470
Well? Say something!

949
01:18:25,400 --> 01:18:29,075
Do something! Be a man!

950
01:18:30,480 --> 01:18:32,436
I already have a butler.

951
01:18:36,640 --> 01:18:40,269
Do something! I don't want this!

952
01:18:40,400 --> 01:18:43,312
I don't! I don't want this!

953
01:18:43,440 --> 01:18:46,557
I don't... I don't want this!

954
01:18:47,680 --> 01:18:52,231
<i>The same conversation as the previous</i>
<i>year, only this time with greater venom.</i>

955
01:18:52,360 --> 01:18:55,989
You've always been afraid of me.
It's not because of my money.

956
01:18:56,120 --> 01:18:58,714
It's basically because you're a coward.

957
01:18:58,840 --> 01:19:02,913
Your pitiful masculinity is so fragile,
you can't stand confrontation,

958
01:19:03,040 --> 01:19:05,315
so you go off with Miss Botsky.

959
01:19:05,440 --> 01:19:07,590
Good night.

960
01:19:23,840 --> 01:19:27,196
<i>As was usual,</i>
<i>I was awakened before dawn.</i>

961
01:19:32,640 --> 01:19:35,359
<i>I let the dogs out, as was customary.</i>

962
01:19:39,360 --> 01:19:44,514
<i>I went back through the bedroom</i>
<i>to my study as quietly as possible.</i>

963
01:19:49,240 --> 01:19:51,800
<i>I did not notice if my wife was in bed.</i>

964
01:19:51,920 --> 01:19:55,390
<i>I did not notice if the light was on</i>
<i>under the bathroom door.</i>

965
01:19:55,520 --> 01:19:58,956
<i>Had it been on, I wouldn't</i>
<i>have given it a thought.</i>

966
01:19:59,080 --> 01:20:03,995
<i>I did my exercises, showered,</i>
<i>and then I called Deborah Knowles.</i>

967
01:20:04,120 --> 01:20:06,918
Well, I mean, it's stable and it's profitable.

968
01:20:07,600 --> 01:20:11,275
<i>Can anyone really believe,</i>
<i>if I was trying to murder my wife,</i>

969
01:20:11,400 --> 01:20:16,394
<i>that I would spend an hour</i>
<i>going over a tedious set of figures?</i>

970
01:20:16,520 --> 01:20:20,433
<i>After the call, I passed through</i>
<i>the bedroom again. It was freezing.</i>

971
01:20:20,560 --> 01:20:23,199
<i>By this time, Sunny</i>
<i>was certainly not in bed.</i>

972
01:20:23,320 --> 01:20:26,756
<i>And I heard water</i>
<i>running in the bathroom.</i>

973
01:20:28,760 --> 01:20:32,150
<i>I had breakfast, walked the dogs,</i>

974
01:20:32,280 --> 01:20:36,592
<i>and, on my return,</i>
<i>asked the children where Mummy was.</i>

975
01:20:36,720 --> 01:20:38,950
Has Mummy had breakfast yet?

976
01:20:39,080 --> 01:20:41,036
We haven't seen her.

977
01:20:44,680 --> 01:20:46,636
Sunny?

978
01:20:47,560 --> 01:20:49,835
<i>Her bathroom was</i>
<i>her private sanctuary.</i>

979
01:20:49,960 --> 01:20:54,556
<i>No one entered it. Except the maid,</i>
<i>of course, to clean up.</i>

980
01:20:54,680 --> 01:20:57,911
<i>Sometimes she stayed there</i>
<i>for hours, or so it seemed.</i>

981
01:20:58,040 --> 01:21:01,555
<i>One can only speculate</i>
<i>what goes on behind a closed door.</i>

982
01:21:01,680 --> 01:21:03,910
Sunny, are you there?

983
01:21:04,600 --> 01:21:07,160
<i>I hesitated even to knock.</i>

984
01:21:09,320 --> 01:21:11,276
Darling?

985
01:21:26,000 --> 01:21:27,956
Sunny?

986
01:21:29,440 --> 01:21:31,396
Oh, God.

987
01:21:32,120 --> 01:21:36,193
<i>Once I'd ascertained she was breathing,</i>
I went to fetch Alexander.

988
01:21:36,840 --> 01:21:40,958
- Why not call an ambulance first?
- Panic, Alan, panic.

989
01:21:41,080 --> 01:21:43,071
I mean, I...

990
01:21:43,200 --> 01:21:46,033
I needed to talk to somebody.

991
01:21:46,160 --> 01:21:52,952
I wasn't worried if she was breathing
normally. It wasn't like the year before.

992
01:21:53,080 --> 01:21:57,358
In retrospect it seems absurd,
but I looked at her upper lip.

993
01:21:57,480 --> 01:22:02,634
She had blood on it. I thought she'd
broken a tooth. That was my concern.

994
01:22:02,760 --> 01:22:08,039
And that's really all I can...
that's really all I can say.

995
01:22:10,240 --> 01:22:13,073
- But is it the truth?
- Of course.

996
01:22:13,200 --> 01:22:17,352
- But not the whole truth.
- I don't know the whole truth.

997
01:22:17,480 --> 01:22:21,917
- I don't know what happened to her.
- I wish I didn't believe you.

998
01:22:22,040 --> 01:22:26,158
It's very hard to trust someone
you don't understand.

999
01:22:27,400 --> 01:22:29,470
You're a very strange man.

1000
01:22:30,520 --> 01:22:32,875
You have no idea.

1001
01:22:40,360 --> 01:22:43,670
- Everybody here?
- Macintosh says he's got bad news.

1002
01:22:46,040 --> 01:22:48,156
There he is.

1003
01:22:59,920 --> 01:23:01,831
Well?

1004
01:23:01,960 --> 01:23:06,272
I found out what the state has.
Their ace in the hole.

1005
01:23:06,400 --> 01:23:08,391
It's you.

1006
01:23:09,480 --> 01:23:10,708
It's me?

1007
01:23:10,840 --> 01:23:14,515
David Marriott taped
all his conversations with you.

1008
01:23:14,640 --> 01:23:16,676
Oh, great.

1009
01:23:16,800 --> 01:23:21,271
The scuttlebutt is,
if we win the case, you go to prison.

1010
01:23:22,240 --> 01:23:24,196
What did I say?

1011
01:23:24,320 --> 01:23:27,278
Good old corrupt Rhode Island.
A friend got me an excerpt.

1012
01:23:27,400 --> 01:23:31,598
<i> The reason I'm here...</i>
<i>My affidavit is inaccurate.</i>

1013
01:23:31,720 --> 01:23:35,998
<i>David, this is bad. It looks bad.</i>
<i>What do you want? More money?</i>

1014
01:23:36,120 --> 01:23:38,190
<i>Can you get more?</i>

1015
01:23:38,320 --> 01:23:40,231
<i>Yeah.</i>

1016
01:23:40,360 --> 01:23:42,954
- That is not what I said.
- It's on tape, Alan.

1017
01:23:43,080 --> 01:23:45,469
I don't care. That's not what I said.

1018
01:23:45,600 --> 01:23:47,716
- What do we do?
- I don't know.

1019
01:23:51,240 --> 01:23:53,151
I'll tell you what we do. We ignore it.

1020
01:23:53,280 --> 01:23:56,272
Alan, with that tape,
it's your whole career.

1021
01:23:57,800 --> 01:23:59,870
I now believe Claus is innocent,

1022
01:24:00,000 --> 01:24:03,993
so we've decided:
no tricks, no technicalities.

1023
01:24:04,120 --> 01:24:09,353
We are going to base our appeal directly
and explicitly on Claus's innocence.

1024
01:24:09,480 --> 01:24:14,429
- Appeals must be based on judicial error.
- The judge should've thrown out the case.

1025
01:24:14,560 --> 01:24:17,836
You can't say there wasn't
sufficient evidence. He was convicted.

1026
01:24:17,960 --> 01:24:20,190
- Good point.
- That's what we are saying.

1027
01:24:20,320 --> 01:24:22,993
If the rules don't work, you change them.

1028
01:24:23,120 --> 01:24:26,829
Red Auerbach changed the jump-ball rule
when the Celtics had a short team.

1029
01:24:26,960 --> 01:24:30,509
But it's dangerous politically.
If the judges feel insulted...

1030
01:24:30,640 --> 01:24:36,636
Wait. State supreme court shouldn't even
look at an appeal based on new evidence.

1031
01:24:36,760 --> 01:24:42,357
Hey, guys. I'll take care of that, OK?
You just leave it to me.

1032
01:24:43,320 --> 01:24:47,677
Look, I know you're all exhausted.
We got four days left.

1033
01:24:47,800 --> 01:24:51,156
What we do now will decide this thing.
Do you wanna win or not?

1034
01:24:51,280 --> 01:24:55,319
- Alan! We've got something.
- We've hit the jackpot.

1035
01:24:55,440 --> 01:24:58,238
Our needles that had
amobarbital and Valium...

1036
01:24:58,360 --> 01:24:59,315
But no insulin.

1037
01:24:59,440 --> 01:25:03,956
Both came back with
false-positive readings for insulin.

1038
01:25:04,440 --> 01:25:06,396
One was 93, the other 282.

1039
01:25:06,520 --> 01:25:10,195
We've knocked out every piece
of their medical case.

1040
01:25:12,520 --> 01:25:16,479
OK, now all they've got left is my neck.

1041
01:25:16,600 --> 01:25:19,273
Anybody know anything
about editing audio tapes?

1042
01:25:28,120 --> 01:25:31,476
Defense! Defense! Come on.

1043
01:25:31,600 --> 01:25:33,909
Come on, baby! Come on, baby!

1044
01:25:40,960 --> 01:25:44,270
- All right, Alan.
- Come on!

1045
01:25:46,040 --> 01:25:48,031
Pass it, Alan.

1046
01:25:48,160 --> 01:25:50,628
Wait a minute. I got it. Where's Raj?

1047
01:25:50,760 --> 01:25:52,830
- He's upstairs.
- Where are you going?

1048
01:25:54,400 --> 01:25:57,198
Raj. Raj, I got it.

1049
01:25:57,320 --> 01:25:59,276
I got it. Remember Maria?

1050
01:26:00,040 --> 01:26:01,792
<i>She could have said it like this:</i>

1051
01:26:01,920 --> 01:26:06,516
Insulin? For what, insulin?

1052
01:26:08,160 --> 01:26:10,355
My lady is not diabetic.

1053
01:26:10,480 --> 01:26:13,950
You see? "My lady is not diabetic."

1054
01:26:14,080 --> 01:26:17,152
She is assuming that the bag is Sunny's.

1055
01:26:17,280 --> 01:26:21,398
Her first reaction, not part of
a legal strategy devised later,

1056
01:26:21,520 --> 01:26:24,557
is that the stuff in the black bag
belonged to Sunny, not Claus.

1057
01:26:24,680 --> 01:26:28,434
Who'd know better than she?
Start writing.

1058
01:26:28,560 --> 01:26:31,597
You are not God! You are a prosecutor!

1059
01:26:31,720 --> 01:26:35,713
Alabama can't execute those Johnson
kids before the Supreme Court rules!

1060
01:26:35,840 --> 01:26:37,398
You heard me right.

1061
01:26:37,520 --> 01:26:41,195
- You got two hours to make Rhode Island.
- You want me to speed?

1062
01:26:41,320 --> 01:26:44,118
No. They'll stop you
and you won't make the deadline.

1063
01:26:44,240 --> 01:26:47,755
I'm telling you right now,
those kids fry, you're next!

1064
01:26:47,880 --> 01:26:49,279
You're damn right!

1065
01:26:49,840 --> 01:26:52,718
<i>Some startling developments</i>
<i>in the von Bulow case.</i>

1066
01:26:52,840 --> 01:26:57,755
<i>Professor Alan Dershowitz had been</i>
<i>accused of paying for falsified testimony,</i>

1067
01:26:57,880 --> 01:27:01,555
<i>but those accusations were discredited</i>
<i>today by the attorney general,</i>

1068
01:27:01,680 --> 01:27:04,399
<i>who announced that</i>
<i>David Marriott's tape was doctored</i>

1069
01:27:04,520 --> 01:27:07,239
<i>and that Marriott is not a reliable witness.</i>

1070
01:27:07,360 --> 01:27:10,716
So, what was he up to, Alan?
Who was he working for?

1071
01:27:10,840 --> 01:27:12,990
Damned if I know.

1072
01:27:15,800 --> 01:27:17,756
Hope they don't think he worked for <i>you.</i>

1073
01:27:17,880 --> 01:27:21,873
- No one's going to...
- Look, I don't think you did it, OK?

1074
01:27:22,000 --> 01:27:25,310
But at the Chinese restaurant,
you did duck the big question.

1075
01:27:25,440 --> 01:27:28,034
Chuck is our Alexandra Isles expert.

1076
01:27:29,200 --> 01:27:34,149
Sunny's aspirin overdose.
Why did she take so many?

1077
01:27:35,080 --> 01:27:38,311
What happened? Sunny had a headache?

1078
01:27:40,320 --> 01:27:44,154
The headache was Alexandra, right?

1079
01:27:48,520 --> 01:27:50,511
Let's hear it, Claus.

1080
01:27:52,200 --> 01:27:54,395
Alexandra was spiteful.

1081
01:27:55,480 --> 01:28:00,395
On the day of Sunny's aspirin overdose,

1082
01:28:00,520 --> 01:28:05,753
she returned some presents
I'd given her, some photographs.

1083
01:28:05,880 --> 01:28:08,633
Love letters.

1084
01:28:08,760 --> 01:28:11,069
She dropped them off in a shopping bag.

1085
01:28:12,160 --> 01:28:14,116
Did Sunny see them?

1086
01:28:14,240 --> 01:28:17,630
Sunny was home. I was not.

1087
01:28:18,760 --> 01:28:22,878
Alexandra neglected
to address the package to me.

1088
01:28:23,000 --> 01:28:26,675
I wanna be left alone with
all those beautiful letters.

1089
01:28:26,800 --> 01:28:30,554
What did you do with those letters?
Why did you write those letters?

1090
01:28:32,080 --> 01:28:35,789
There's a big difference
between knowing about an affair

1091
01:28:35,920 --> 01:28:39,151
and having love letters
crammed down your throat.

1092
01:28:40,880 --> 01:28:44,873
It seems that Sunny did care
about your affair. She cared a lot.

1093
01:28:48,440 --> 01:28:50,874
Why didn't you tell us?

1094
01:28:51,000 --> 01:28:52,956
Everything was open-book.

1095
01:28:54,120 --> 01:28:58,159
"Get the best experts."
"I'm not afraid of the truth."

1096
01:29:02,280 --> 01:29:06,193
Looks to me like Alexandra
tried to force Sunny into suicide.

1097
01:29:08,280 --> 01:29:10,316
Or they plotted it together.

1098
01:29:11,560 --> 01:29:15,109
Either way, he's protecting Alexandra
because he still loves her.

1099
01:29:15,240 --> 01:29:17,800
And why not? Hey, she's a babe.

1100
01:29:20,560 --> 01:29:22,790
Of course I still love her.

1101
01:29:24,840 --> 01:29:26,796
And hate her.

1102
01:29:28,120 --> 01:29:32,159
Alexandra, Sunny, Andrea...

1103
01:29:34,960 --> 01:29:36,996
I love them all.

1104
01:29:44,040 --> 01:29:46,838
<i> Being a human being</i>
<i>is very literal.</i>

1105
01:29:46,960 --> 01:29:51,909
<i>You're trapped. Time moves</i>
<i>in only one direction: forward.</i>

1106
01:29:52,040 --> 01:29:55,749
<i>It's stupid and boring</i>
<i>and results in a lot of silliness.</i>

1107
01:29:55,880 --> 01:29:58,599
<i>Example: the legal process.</i>

1108
01:30:00,080 --> 01:30:05,234
<i>In this particular case, a vast amount</i>
<i>of time, effort and money was spent</i>

1109
01:30:05,360 --> 01:30:10,309
<i>trying to determine what happened on</i>
<i>those two nights so close to Christmas,</i>

1110
01:30:10,440 --> 01:30:15,833
<i>December 26, 1979, December 20, 1980.</i>

1111
01:30:16,640 --> 01:30:18,596
<i>Happened right here.</i>

1112
01:30:19,920 --> 01:30:26,871
<i>Even now, it all looks the same,</i>
<i>feels the same, smells the same.</i>

1113
01:30:27,880 --> 01:30:33,193
<i>If you could just go back in time</i>
<i>and take a peek, you'd know.</i>

1114
01:30:34,400 --> 01:30:36,755
<i>And all this would be unnecessary.</i>

1115
01:30:36,880 --> 01:30:38,836
All rise!

1116
01:30:41,960 --> 01:30:45,794
Hear ye, hear ye. All persons having
business before the Supreme Court

1117
01:30:45,920 --> 01:30:50,869
holding in province within and for the
State of Rhode Island may now draw near.

1118
01:30:51,000 --> 01:30:54,675
<i>Then again, everyone enjoys a circus.</i>

1119
01:30:56,280 --> 01:30:58,236
Be seated.

1120
01:30:59,800 --> 01:31:03,759
If the appellant is ready,
you may proceed.

1121
01:31:03,880 --> 01:31:05,996
Oral argument will be made

1122
01:31:06,120 --> 01:31:09,908
by out-of-state counsel,
Professor Alan Dershowitz.

1123
01:31:18,840 --> 01:31:23,118
Your Honors, you may not
like Claus von Bulow.

1124
01:31:23,240 --> 01:31:28,473
You may think he is guilty of something.
But I am here to tell you he is innocent.

1125
01:31:28,600 --> 01:31:30,955
- Our new evidence...
- Professor.

1126
01:31:31,080 --> 01:31:35,756
You know there is no case which allows
you to introduce new evidence on appeal.

1127
01:31:35,880 --> 01:31:42,069
There is one, Your Honor.
And you wrote it: <i>Derek.</i>

1128
01:31:42,200 --> 01:31:45,829
In <i>Derek,</i> you yourself said

1129
01:31:45,960 --> 01:31:50,351
that a case based on
circumstantial theory rather than fact

1130
01:31:50,480 --> 01:31:54,155
only stands up if no other theory
makes sense.

1131
01:31:54,280 --> 01:31:57,750
The only way to show a better theory
is to present it.

1132
01:32:03,800 --> 01:32:06,872
Get on with it, counselor.

1133
01:32:07,000 --> 01:32:09,912
The first issue is the encrusted needle.

1134
01:32:10,720 --> 01:32:13,518
<i>I hope you will have the courage</i>
<i>to free an innocent man</i>

1135
01:32:13,640 --> 01:32:16,074
<i>and remedy a grave injustice.</i>

1136
01:32:16,200 --> 01:32:20,159
This will never work.
Too smart for his own good.

1137
01:32:20,280 --> 01:32:25,513
Alan says it will work.
If the prosecutor takes the bait.

1138
01:32:25,640 --> 01:32:27,995
What do you mean, "bait"?

1139
01:32:28,120 --> 01:32:30,554
Argues the evidence.

1140
01:32:30,680 --> 01:32:35,310
Your Honors, introduction
of new evidence on appeal

1141
01:32:35,440 --> 01:32:40,719
violates every principle of
jurisprudence, every statute,

1142
01:32:40,840 --> 01:32:43,434
every precedent, every rule of ethics.

1143
01:32:43,560 --> 01:32:45,152
He's nailing us.

1144
01:32:45,280 --> 01:32:50,308
I am not going to stand before you
and argue Mr. von Bulow's guilt.

1145
01:32:51,960 --> 01:32:57,637
However, I have no choice but to address
Mr. Dershowitz's arguments one by one.

1146
01:32:58,640 --> 01:33:02,872
- Bingo.
- First, the encrusted needle.

1147
01:33:03,840 --> 01:33:08,152
So, now it's up to the judges.
Tell me what you really think.

1148
01:33:08,280 --> 01:33:12,432
I think it's easier to love somebody
than to live with them.

1149
01:33:14,000 --> 01:33:17,310
Love is fantasy. Living is work.

1150
01:33:17,440 --> 01:33:20,716
I'll say. And those people
don't like to work.

1151
01:33:20,840 --> 01:33:25,311
But if you don't do the work, the love dies,
and nobody wants to deal with that one.

1152
01:33:25,440 --> 01:33:27,590
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

1153
01:33:27,720 --> 01:33:33,590
The love died, Sunny couldn't accept it...
so Claus tried to kill her?

1154
01:33:33,720 --> 01:33:35,711
- Maybe.
- I don't agree.

1155
01:33:36,840 --> 01:33:40,230
Face it. All we had to do was
prove the state made a lousy case.

1156
01:33:40,360 --> 01:33:44,148
We didn't prove Claus was innocent.
We couldn't, and he probably isn't.

1157
01:33:44,280 --> 01:33:47,829
- You mean you think?
- So he didn't inject Sunny with insulin.

1158
01:33:47,960 --> 01:33:50,428
So what? First coma, no problem.

1159
01:33:50,560 --> 01:33:55,839
The attending doctor thought it was
caused by hypoglycemia. All right.

1160
01:33:55,960 --> 01:33:59,873
But what about the second coma?
I mean, why does Claus act so guilty?

1161
01:34:00,000 --> 01:34:03,436
Wouldn't any man feel guilty
if his wife was suicidal?

1162
01:34:03,560 --> 01:34:08,793
Yeah. So maybe she took the sleeping
pills with the intention of killing herself.

1163
01:34:08,920 --> 01:34:12,151
But how did she end up
lying on a marble floor

1164
01:34:12,280 --> 01:34:14,953
in a freezing bathroom
with her head under the toilet?

1165
01:34:15,080 --> 01:34:17,036
How about this?

1166
01:35:02,560 --> 01:35:05,120
<i>Sunny wakes up miserable.</i>

1167
01:35:09,480 --> 01:35:13,439
<i>Second marriage is over,</i>
<i>children are leaving home.</i>

1168
01:35:13,560 --> 01:35:15,516
<i>What's to live for?</i>

1169
01:37:22,480 --> 01:37:25,711
But when she was found, her nightgown
was hiked over her waist.

1170
01:37:25,840 --> 01:37:28,718
Exactly. How did it get there?

1171
01:37:29,600 --> 01:37:33,513
<i> OK, let's say she's standing</i>
<i>at the sink. She has to pee.</i>

1172
01:37:33,640 --> 01:37:36,871
<i>At exactly the same instant,</i>
<i>the drugs hit,</i>

1173
01:37:37,000 --> 01:37:40,310
<i>her body convulses,</i>
<i>she grabs the nightgown.</i>

1174
01:37:44,640 --> 01:37:47,279
- I don't buy that.
- It does seem far-fetched.

1175
01:37:48,000 --> 01:37:49,797
- So is the truth sometimes.
- Bull!

1176
01:37:49,920 --> 01:37:55,313
I think she took the drugs the previous
night. Maybe he saw her take them.

1177
01:37:55,440 --> 01:37:58,671
<i>Or she told him she was going to</i>
<i>before they fell asleep.</i>

1178
01:38:07,000 --> 01:38:10,549
<i>This time, he wants her to succeed.</i>

1179
01:38:19,640 --> 01:38:21,596
Sunny?

1180
01:38:46,880 --> 01:38:49,952
<i> Maybe there's some way</i>
<i>he can help her along.</i>

1181
01:38:50,080 --> 01:38:53,277
<i>Of course. The open window.</i>

1182
01:38:54,160 --> 01:38:56,594
<i>Zero degrees.</i>

1183
01:38:56,720 --> 01:38:59,632
<i>But somebody might see her there.</i>

1184
01:38:59,760 --> 01:39:04,276
<i>The action of dragging her would</i>
<i>naturally pull up the nightgown.</i>

1185
01:39:32,080 --> 01:39:35,436
<i>In this cold, how long</i>
<i>could she survive?</i>

1186
01:39:54,600 --> 01:39:57,114
<i>Remember what Sunny said?</i>

1187
01:39:57,240 --> 01:40:01,711
<i>"I would've been better off.</i>
<i>You would've been better off. "</i>

1188
01:40:06,120 --> 01:40:08,509
...because the law is a blunt instrument.

1189
01:40:08,640 --> 01:40:12,235
It is not a rapier. It is a cudgel.

1190
01:40:12,360 --> 01:40:16,353
Tomorrow, death penalty. Which
reminds me of the comedian who said

1191
01:40:16,480 --> 01:40:20,871
"Why do they call it the death penalty?
It's no penalty. You're out of the game!"

1192
01:40:29,400 --> 01:40:31,550
- Good news.
- And more good news.

1193
01:40:31,680 --> 01:40:34,319
- The decision came?
- They just announced it.

1194
01:40:34,440 --> 01:40:36,590
- Five-zip.
- We murdered 'em.

1195
01:40:36,720 --> 01:40:39,109
- Grounds?
- They got the Brillhoffer notes.

1196
01:40:39,240 --> 01:40:41,913
And that guilty-man's argument,
search and seizure.

1197
01:40:42,040 --> 01:40:44,235
- Federal or state?
- Both.

1198
01:40:44,360 --> 01:40:49,229
If it's federal, they could appeal, but
as it's Rhode Island, they can't. We win.

1199
01:40:49,360 --> 01:40:52,033
Don't get too excited till
we see Brillhoffer's notes.

1200
01:40:52,160 --> 01:40:57,234
We destroyed their medical case, but their
witnesses still carry emotional weight.

1201
01:40:57,360 --> 01:41:02,115
Unless the Brillhoffer notes show
that they've changed their stories.

1202
01:41:02,720 --> 01:41:04,676
Good afternoon, sir.

1203
01:41:06,080 --> 01:41:08,548
- Let me get that for you.
- Thank you.

1204
01:41:21,920 --> 01:41:24,514
- You have Brillhoffer's notes?
- Yes.

1205
01:41:24,640 --> 01:41:26,596
- Well?
- They're not what we hoped.

1206
01:41:26,720 --> 01:41:28,711
I knew it.

1207
01:41:31,000 --> 01:41:32,956
They're much better.

1208
01:41:34,360 --> 01:41:37,716
No one mentioned insulin
when they first talked to Brillhoffer.

1209
01:41:37,840 --> 01:41:43,153
Plus, Maria told him that, when
she supposedly first saw insulin,

1210
01:41:43,280 --> 01:41:47,239
she couldn't even read any of the
labels. They were all scraped off.

1211
01:41:47,360 --> 01:41:49,555
- What does this mean?
- It means...

1212
01:41:49,680 --> 01:41:52,877
that if there is a second trial,
we can be confident.

1213
01:41:53,000 --> 01:41:56,436
Both the medical case and
their witnesses are now highly suspect.

1214
01:41:56,560 --> 01:41:58,357
Ah!

1215
01:42:18,080 --> 01:42:21,595
Darling, this is Alan Dershowitz.

1216
01:42:21,720 --> 01:42:23,438
Yes, I know. Hello.

1217
01:42:23,560 --> 01:42:27,235
Alan tells me...
Well, things look very hopeful.

1218
01:42:28,880 --> 01:42:32,509
I knew it would come out all right.
Thank you.

1219
01:42:35,560 --> 01:42:38,279
Yes, Alan, thank you.
I am eternally grateful.

1220
01:42:38,400 --> 01:42:42,359
Hey, this means we'll be getting back
your bail. A million dollars.

1221
01:42:42,480 --> 01:42:45,153
I know I still owe you, Alan.

1222
01:42:46,080 --> 01:42:48,799
Please send me your bill.

1223
01:42:48,920 --> 01:42:54,790
And maybe when you're in New York
we can meet for lunch. I'd enjoy that.

1224
01:42:56,000 --> 01:43:00,152
One thing, Claus. Legally,
this was an important victory.

1225
01:43:00,280 --> 01:43:02,669
Morally, you're on your own.

1226
01:43:14,400 --> 01:43:20,839
<i> Claus von Bulow was given a</i>
<i>second trial and acquitted on both counts.</i>

1227
01:43:21,720 --> 01:43:26,350
<i>This is all you can know,</i>
<i>all you can be told.</i>

1228
01:43:27,640 --> 01:43:31,997
<i>When you get where I am,</i>
<i>you will know the rest.</i>

1229
01:43:34,480 --> 01:43:42,398
Claus von Bulow is still
married to Sunny von Bulow.
He is presently living
and working in London.

1230
01:43:42,520 --> 01:43:46,308
The Johnson brothers
remain on death row.

1231
01:43:46,440 --> 01:43:51,514
Sunny von Bulow has not spoken
since she fell into her final coma.

1232
01:43:51,640 --> 01:44:03,233
This film is based upon Alan Dershowitz's
book <i>Reversal Of Fortune</i>
and public records.
Dialogue and certain events
and characters contained in the film
were created for
the purpose of dramatization.

1233
01:44:03,360 --> 01:44:05,510
Two packs of Vantage, please.

1234
01:44:13,040 --> 01:44:17,033
- Anything else?
- Yes, a vial of insulin.

1235
01:44:24,040 --> 01:44:25,996
Just kidding.

1236
01:46:36,720 --> 01:46:39,678
Visiontext Subtitles:
Tram Nguyen Zelniker

